http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: More complex cable systems imported from the Telegeography data are represented as Cable Groups, with their constituent segments represented as Cables. A given Cable Group tags all of its related Cables.

Trans-Pacific Cable 4 was put in the water in 1991, only a few years after TPC-3 was laid, yet it doubled the capacity of the earlier system. As the first fiber cable that linked directly from the USA to Japan, it was also the last system to be landed on Canada's west coast. After it was withdrawn from service in 2003, the Port Alberni station ceased to operate transoceanic systems.

The Southern Cross Cable Network was designed as an Internet-based cable that, at the time, would be the fastest and most straightforward route from Australia and New Zealand to the United States. Just as Southern Cross was being put in the water, the cable market collapsed – this was brought on by a combination of the excess capacity offered by the numerous cable systems laid in the late 1990s. The timing of Southern Cross was “perfect,” as its builders recollect, poised on the crest of the cable boom: if they'd started a little bit later, it likely wouldn't have happened.

SeaMeWe-2, laid in 1994, was one of the first optical fiber systems in Southeast Asia and it set records for cable length. Its technical advances achieved capacities 15 times that of its coaxial predecessor SeaMeWe-1. However, the complexities and costs of the project meant that fewer countries were ultimately linked to the network.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/title.value: ASEAN Optical Fibre Submarine Cable Network (AOFSCN)

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In the early 1990s, the member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN, banded together to set up this cable system, nicknamed "Asia's Fiber Glove" by one news report. It stretched from Brunei to Singapore, north to Malaysia, and then onward to Thailand and the Philippines. When the APCN cable was laid, this created a redundant loop, ensuring traffic would continue even in the case of a cable break.

Completed in 1964, Trans-Pacific Cable 1 was the first coaxial cable to link Japan and the U.S. via landing sites in Guam and Hawaii. It was also part of a global communications network that linked tracking stations, command centers, and other infrastructure during the Apollo missions, including the moon landing in 1969. TPC-1 carried voice signals across the ocean for twenty-six years and, since 1990, the decommissioned cable has been used to study earthquakes.

The Australia-Japan Cable (AJC) links the two countries via Guam. When it was completed in 2001, it became “Australia’s largest connection yet to the global information highways,” according to an industry newsletter. The cable reaches depths of over 9,000 meters and forms a “collapsed ring” structure with twin lines spanning each leg of the system. A private company owned by Japanese and Australian telecoms was set up to design, build, and operate the cable until its projected retirement in 2026.

When it entered service in 2002, the TGN (Tyco Global Network) cable between Japan and the U.S. offered the highest capacity of any Pacific crossing. Messages travel along this route in as little as .022 seconds. TGN was acquired by the massive Indian company, Tata Communications, in 2005.

Although undersea fiber-optic cables were introduced in the region in the 1980s, the TVH cable, completed in 1996, was the first system to link Thailand, Vietnam, and Hong Kong with a communications channel equivalent to 80,000 simultaneous phone calls.

Asia-America Gateway (AAG), opened in 2009, was the first high-bandwidth optical cable to provide a direct link between Southeast Asia and California (via the Philippines, Guam, and Hawaii). Positioned further south than other trans-Pacific routes, AAG avoids the seismically active areas near Taiwan where earthquakes are known to cause cable disruptions.

The Asia-Pacific Cable Network links several nodes around the China Seas. Initially completed in 2002, it has suffered multiple failures caused by undersea earthquakes and structural faults despite the cable’s “self-healing ring” design. Fortunately, the network's disruption has not typically halted Internet access, due to area's many redundant pathways. Nevertheless, the Internet can slow to a crawl when the APCN-2 is down.

Joining Sydney and Auckland in 1992, the Tasman-2 cable was a major achievement for Australia and New Zealand, and most of the system was manufactured within these countries. The cable's pioneering significance has not kept pace with recent innovations, however, as its present capacity fills only 1% of the company’s regional traffic.

To build GOKI, AT&T commissioned two Japanese cable companies to pull up 800 miles of retired underwater networks, including portions of TPC-5. These fragments were then reengineered and combined with new fibers to create a much faster optical link between Japan and Guam.

The PPC-1 cable, laid in 2009 to connect Australia, Guam, and Papua New Guinea, has enough capacity to carry simultaneous phone calls from the entire population of Australia – over twenty million people. Countries don't need to have an extensive network in part due to the enormous capacity of fiber optics.

This two-part cable system links American Samoa and Samoa to Keawaula, Hawaii, where it joins networks reaching the U.S. mainland, Southeast Asia, and Australia. To lower costs, the system repurposed sections of the PacRim East cable between Hawaii and New Zealand, built in the 1990s as one of the first fiber-optic trans-Pacific links and retired in 2007. Despite being nearly 20 years old, the cable provides more than enough capacity for these small island groups.

Established in 1997, the Asia-Pacific Cable Network (APCN) spans more than 7,400 miles and connects Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, Indonesia, Singapore, Malaysia, and Thailand. A telecom consortium (including AT&T, Alcatel-Lucent, and KDD Submarine Cable Systems) owns this regional trunk-and-branch network.

Part of an alternate route between European and Asian hubs, the HSCS first connected Japan’s Hokkaido and Russia’s Sakhalin in 2008. While the route boasts improved speeds and latency handling over the old network pathways, its construction in large part responds to the outages caused in 2006 by an undersea earthquake in Taiwan and the subsequent need for more redundancies in the region's cable connections.

In 2012, Telekom Malysia (TM) contracted with the Japanese company NTT Communications to run two of the six optical fiber pairs of the Asia Submarine-cable Express (ASE) system connecting Malaysia, Singapore, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and Japan. The portion of the network owned by TM is branded Cahaya Malaysia (“cahaya” is the Indonesian word for “light”).

Entering service in 1997, the FLAG (Fiber-Optic Link Around the Globe) Europe-Asia cable system connects the United Kingdom with Japan via more than a dozen landing sites. The cable, now operated by an Indian telecom, was the subject of a 1996 Wired magazine article by cyberpunk author Neal Stephenson in which he traveled to “six countries and four continents trying to get a grip on this longest, fastest, mother of all wires.”

Entering service in 1990 and since decommissioned, the Hong Kong-Japan-Korea (HJK) cable system connected Deep Water Bay, Hong Kong and Chikura, Japan with a branch to Jeju Island, South Korea. It was built by Fujitsu Limited (with AT&T as a subcontractor) and, along with the TPC-3, GPT, and HonTai cables, formed a “redundant fiber loop” in the South Pacific.

In the late 1980s Trans-Pacific Cable 3, a joint venture by AT&T, Japan’s KDD, and several other companies, was one of the first optical cables to cross the Pacific. With TPC-3, “fiber-optic technology now links Europe, North America, and Asia,” proclaimed the New York Times in April 1989. This offered several advantages: it was a second or two faster than satellite transmissions, as well as more secure, cheaper to operate, and less prone to interference than copper lines.

MIC-1 is only 70 km long, short enough to not need a repeater. Like many other cables that connect Singapore and Batam, it was designed to further development and attract Western investment in this international free trade zone.

The South Africa-Far East (SAFE) cable system, built in 2002 by a U.S. company, traverses the Indian Ocean on a path similar to the one taken by Portuguese explorers in the fifteenth century. By joining the SAT-3/WASC cable at Melkbosstrand, South Africa, SAFE provides a direct optical fiber link between Western Europe and Malaysia.

EAC-C2C represents the merger of the EAC (East Asia Crossing) and C2C (City-to-City) cable networks, completed in 2007 by Pacnet. Together, they form Asia’s largest privately owned cable system with a total of seventeen landing sites across Japan, Korea, China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and Singapore.
Laid by the Dutch East Indies Government in 1859, this cable was intended to help connect the Dutch colonies in the region.

The optical underwater Asia-Pacific Cable (APC) was completed in 1993 and linked Japan, Taiwan, Malaysia, and Singapore until its decommissioning in 2006. Run by an international consortium, the APC promised to create a “fiber backbone for the region’s burgeoning telecommunications infrastructure,” explains an industry newsletter from 1991.

Built in 2009 by French telecom subsidiaries, this 1,000 km cable connects French Réunion with Madagascar and Mauritius. In 2012 it was expanded to include Kenya, providing an important node in the African broadband network.
When i2icn was completed in 2002, the network offered more capacity than any other undersea system in the region.

Completed in 2000, the consortium-owned China-U.S. Cable Network was the first direct cable route between the two countries. It consists of dual Pacific crossings, forming a ring structure with connections along the west coast of the U.S. and between several Southeast Asian hubs. Only a year after it entered service, however, the anchor of a fishing boat off Chongming Island disrupted much of the traffic between China and the U.S..

In 2012, a consortium of telecom companies led by China Unicom signed a construction and maintenance agreement for the Asia-Pacific Gateway (APG) cable system, due to open in 2015. The system is specially routed to avoid areas prone to seismic activity while providing additional capacity along the region’s existing international networks.

A short 72.9 km link across the Singapore Strait joins these two cities by cable, though they are already economically and politically connected via the Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle free trade zone.

Constructed in 2008 by a consortium of six telecom companies, the Trans-Pacific Express (TPE) cable is a major link between sites in the South China Sea (China, South Korea, and Taiwan) and the west coast of the United States. An extension to Japan opened in 2010. It greatly increased connection speeds across the Pacific, bringing them up to those found in trans-Atlantic cables.

Reusing old cables from PacRim West, APNG-2 links Australia and Papua New Guinea. Because of this project, internet speeds increased by a factor of 7 in the latter country. Additional cable capacity has been leased to major mining companies active in the region.

When it was finished in December 2005, the consortium-owned Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 4 cable provided both additional bandwidth and greater redundancy along the bulk of the previous-generation SeaMeWe-3 line between the Mediterranean and Singapore. SeaMeWe-3, however, extends significantly further to points in China, Japan, Australia, the U.K., and Germany, among others.

Planned and built over the course of seven years, this cable sponsored by the New Caledonia Postal and Telecommunications Office (OPT-NC) joined the French territory to a hub in North Sydney in 2008. It’s named after the southern super-continent that broke away from Pangaea roughly 200 million years ago and which included what are now Africa, Australia, South America, and Antarctica. While it doesn’t bundle multiple continents, the cable did bring New Caledonia into the modern underwater network, boosting local connection speeds well beyond existing satellite links.

Linking their country to the US lines in Hawai’i, Australia’s largest telecommunications provider, Telstra, built this cable in 2008 at the estimated cost of $300 million AUD. As Telstra's COO notes, the cable serves to ”significantly reduce Australia's reliance on foreign-owned companies in order to compete globally."
This cable extends Tata Communications’ global network into Southeast Asia, connecting major hubs in Singapore and Hong Kong with smaller stations in Vietnam and the Philippines.

Having built two previous cable systems across the Sea of Japan, Rostelecom and KDDI launched the dual-line Russia-Japan Cable Network in September 2008, only a few months after competing telecom operators established a northern link from Hokkaido to Sakhalin. Combined with Russia’s terrestrial cable system, RJCN boasts a latency of less than 200 milliseconds between Tokyo and London, faster than both Pacific/U.S. and Indian Ocean routes.

The consortium-owned Southeast Asia Japan Cable (SJC) runs from Singapore to Japan, with branch connections to Thailand, Brunei, the Philippines, Hong Kong, and China. Intense demand along the communication route prompted capacity upgrades less than a year after it was built in 2013.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/title.value: FLAG North Asia Loop/REACH North Asia Loop

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: FLAG North Asian Loop a.k.a. Reach North Asian Loop, jointly developed by India’s Global Cloud Xchange (formerly FLAG Telecom) and China’s Reach Global Services, has one of the largest cable capacities in Asia. The system’s two fiber loops connect Hong Kong, Taiwan, South Korea, and Japan and were completed in 2001 and 2002.
Owned by the Vanuatu-based telecom company Interchange and installed by France’s Alcatel-Lucent, this cable stretches over 700 miles between Port Vila and Suva, Fiji.

Though it was only activated in 2013, this is the first direct fiber-optic connection between Taiwan and Mainland China. Previously, signal traffic was routed through other hubs in regional networks. To some, the cable represents a major step toward greater economic cooperation across the Taiwan Strait.

Built within a year of breaking ground, TIC broke records for its speedy construction. As it linked Singapore to India along a historic, well-traveled cable route, its commentators noted that the project “spells promising times ahead for the international bandwidth market for India.”

Stretching a total of 24,000 miles between 39 landing sites, Southeast Asia-Middle East-Western Europe 3 (SeaMeWe-3) is more than twice as long as its intercontinental predecessor, SeaMeWe-2. The optical cable system was commissioned in 2000 by an international consortium of nearly 100 corporate investors.

A partnership between Korea Telecom, Japan Telecom, NTT Communications, and the Kyushu Electric Power Company, this cable entered service ahead of the 2002 World Cup, co-hosted by the two countries. From Busan, the system makes two, 150-mile journeys across the Korea Strait to Kyushu, a trade route that dates back to the 14th century.

Constructed through an early-2000s partnership between Singapore’s SingTel, the Communications Authority of Thailand, and Telkom Indonesia, this cable links the three countries across the South China Sea.

This cable links two U.S. and two Japanese cities in a closed loop. Originally a joint venture by several telecom companies, Pacific Crossing (and its operating company) was sold to Japan’s NTT Communications in 2009. Both the northern Pacific route and the western segment along the Japanese coast were damaged during the 2011 earthquake.

This cable, which links Tonga to Fiji and the entire Southern Cross trans-Pacific network, was completed in August 2013 with major funding from the Asian Development Bank and World Bank. Run by the government-owned Tonga Cable Limited, it is part of a larger effort to connect smaller island nations in the Pacific.

Named after its owner, Hannon Armstrong, and operator Truestone, this system initially linked Guam to the Ronald Regan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site in the Marshall Islands and was funded by the U.S. Army. In 2010, extensions were made to Majuro and the Federated States of Micronesia, greatly increasing speeds over existing satellite transmissions.

In the 1920s, the Pacific Cable Board lay a higher capacity system, a "loaded cable" that eventually transmitted 150 words/minute directly from Suva, Fiji to Auckland, bypassing Norfolk Island. Thus began the era in the South Pacific of skipping over intermediate islands to ensure more "direct" routing.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/title.value: Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) submarine cable

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The ASEAN cable was laid in several sections, with its first links connecting the Philippines and Indonesia to Singapore, in 1978 and 1980, respectively. The final section of the cable was inaugurated in 1983 by “a three-way conversation among the Communications Ministers of Malaysia, Singapore, and Thailand,” reports the New Straits Times. With landing stations in all five countries, the cable had a capacity of 1,680 telephone lines and carried telegraph and telex messages as well. But the inauguration placed the most emphasis on the cable system’s political significance. It represented “the unity, understanding, and cooperation among the five ASEAN nations” and “exemplified their strong dedication to work towards common objectives beneficial to all.”

Launched with great fanfare in 2008, the Matrix Cable System promised to mark “the elimination of the digital divide in Indonesia” by linking Jakarta, Singapore, and Batam. The price for Internet services has fallen significantly due to the cable's increase in network capacity.

Completed in 1989, GPT was an extension of TPC-3 cable, and provided Taiwan and the Philippines a link to the transpacific fiber network. It was withdrawn from service a mere 14 years later and presently serves as a monitoring tool for oceanographic science.

Laid in 1984 as a replacement for the COMPAC system, ANZCAN was the last major transpacific coaxial system. After this, fiber-optic technologies drastically increased the amount of capacity that could be carried and made the system obsolete by 2002.

Sanford Fleming and the Canadian Government mobilized arguments about security to establish the first transpacific cable system in 1902, creating a foundational route for all north-south Pacific traffic. This system mastered the scale of the globe: the Pacific Cable Board line between Bamfield, Canada and Fanning Island was then the longest undersea cable in the world. This system also required new expenditures for infrastructure and planning. A new 8,000 ton ship, the Colonia, had to be constructed specifically for the line.
